<br>
I never just &quot;hit autoattack, etc.&quot; I was always acutely aware of my own and others' proximities to the mob and was constantly adjusting my own proximity to use that as an aid to keeping aggro. If the situation allowed for it, I would not taunt from behind to regain aggro, but strafe around and make sure I was between the mob and its current target. Fighting was a dynamic dance. I kept up a running information with the person in charge of crowd control about the status and &quot;waiting order&quot; of adds. Often, our group was making decisions on the fly about the combat, adjusting roles and fighting styles. In many of my groups, I was directing the rate and flow of combat, adjusting our position in the environment through my control of the mob(s). <br>
<br>
But then, I only got to 54. I avoided the tedium of raids. And I often fought with groups that were pushing themselves in places where they would have gotten creamed if they weren't a tight unit with great communication. I did A LOT of pulling. So, I guess, that's another suggestion to make being a warrior interesting. <br>
<br>
The two big reasons I stopped being a warrior had nothing to do with being bored with the class. The greatest reason was the attitude of other players toward the warrior class and the decision by a large percentage of players that paladins were the only tanks worth having (or so I got told over and over). The second reason has to do with my own play style. I don't like getting gifts and I'm perpetually poor. Makes playing a gear-dependent class immensely frustrating.<br>
<br>
But I would never call being a warrior boring. At least not the way it CAN be played. Sitting on your behind, standing up, casting, sitting down again...bleh. THAT's much more boring.<br>
<br>
